    {
      "Module Name": "6-Axis IMU and Sensor Interface",
      "Function Description": "Integrates a 6-axis Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) for motion tracking and sensor data acquisition, interfaced with the MCU for real-time data processing in IoT applications.",
      "Signal Sources": "I2C clock and data signals from the ESP32-WROOM-32E, power from the 3.3V supply.",
      "Signal Destinations": "Accelerometer and gyroscope data sent via I2C to the ESP32-WROOM-32E for further processing and transmission.",
      "Implementation Logic": "The IMU module (e.g., MPU6050) is connected to the ESP32 via I2C bus, with pull-up resistors on SDA and SCL lines, and powered by the 3.3V rail from the power management block.",
      "Signal Chain": "The signal chain begins with the 3.3V power supply from the ESP32-WROOM-32E's 3V3 pin (Pin 2) or an external source, which powers the LSM6DSMTR IMU module. The IMU requires VDD (Pin 8) for core power and VDDIO (Pin 5) for I/O levels, both at 3.3V. The ESP32 generates I2C clock (SCL) and data (SDA) signals from its GPIO22 (Pin 36) and GPIO21 (Pin 33) pins, respectively. These signals connect to the IMU's SCL (Pin 13) and SDA (Pin 14) pins, forming a complete I2C bus for communication. Pull-up resistors (not in library) are needed on SDA and SCL lines to 3.3V for proper I2C operation. The IMU's interrupt pins INT1 (Pin 4) and INT2 (Pin 9) can be optionally connected to ESP32 GPIO pins for event-driven data acquisition. Ground connections are established from the ESP32's GND pins (e.g., Pin 1, 15, 38) to the IMU's GND pins (Pin 6, 7). Data flows from the IMU's accelerometer and gyroscope sensors through its internal ADC and processing, then transmitted via I2C to the ESP32 for real-time processing and potential transmission over Wi-Fi/Bluetooth.",
      "Recommended Components": [
        {
