    {
      "Module Name": "Automatic Download and Reset Circuit",
      "Function Description": "Automates the firmware flashing process by toggling the ESP32's EN (Reset) and IO0 pins based on DTR and RTS signals from the USB-to-serial converter, eliminating manual button presses.",
      "Signal Sources": "DTR and RTS signals from the CP2102N USB-to-serial converter.",
      "Signal Destinations": "EN and IO0 pins of the ESP32-WROOM-32E module to control reset and boot modes during programming.",
      "Implementation Logic": "Uses logic gates or transistors to combine DTR and RTS signals, generating pulses that drive EN and IO0 pins low/high as needed to put the ESP32 into bootloader mode and reset it automatically during serial uploads.",
      "Signal Chain": "The signal chain begins with the Micro-USB connector providing 5V power and USB data lines. The 5V from USB pin 1 is regulated to 3.3V by the AMS1117 LDO to power the CP2102 and ESP32. The USB D+ and D- lines connect to the CP2102 for USB-to-UART conversion. The CP2102 generates DTR (pin 28) and RTS (pin 24) signals, which are active-low UART control outputs. These signals drive the gates of two 2N7002 MOSFETs. The DTR signal controls the MOSFET connected to ESP32 EN pin (pin 3), pulling it low when DTR is low to reset the ESP32. The RTS signal controls the MOSFET connected to ESP32 IO0 pin (pin 25), pulling it low when RTS is low to set boot mode. The CP2102 TXD (pin 26) and RXD (pin 25) connect to ESP32 RXD0 (pin 34) and TXD0 (pin 35) for UART communication. The ESP32 operates on 3.3V from the AMS1117, with EN and IO0 controlled by the MOSFETs to automate firmware flashing.",
